{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, one of the Old English Elegies, the compound *mægþumgyfa* (\"treasure-giver\" to retainers or a warrior-band) appears as a near-equivalent to *beag-gyfa* (\"ring-giver\"), both evoking a lord whose authority flows through gifts to his men.[^1]\n\n> Hwær cwōm mægþumgyfa?  \n> (\"Where has the treasure-giver gone?\")[^2]\n\nThe modern English word *lord* (from OE *hlāford*, \"loaf-ward\") does indeed obscure this social structure. It connotes hierarchical authority but is silent on the Germanic *comitatus* bond—the lord's stream of rings, treasure, and feasting as the literal currency of loyalty, without which the retainers scatter and the hall falls silent.[^3] A *beag-gyfa* or *mægþumgyfa* is not just a superior but a generous patron whose gifts (*beag*, *mægþ*, *sinc*) sustain the warrior-band's cohesion amid *wyrd*'s ruin; translating it flatly as \"lord\" erases this performative, material reciprocity so vital to the elegiac lament.",
